        lesson: "<p>Common stock is recorded at par value with excess to APIC. No-par stock records the entire amount to Common Stock unless a stated value exists. Preferred stock may be cumulative, participating, convertible, or callable. Cumulative preferred dividends in arrears must be paid before any common dividends.</p><p>Treasury stock (cost method): debit Treasury Stock at reacquisition cost (contra-equity). Reissued above cost: credit APIC-Treasury Stock for excess. Reissued below cost: debit APIC-TS first (to extent available), then debit Retained Earnings for remainder. Treasury stock is NEVER an asset.</p><p>Cash dividends reduce retained earnings on declaration date. Small stock dividends (under 20-25%) use fair market value: debit RE for FMV, credit Common Stock at par, credit APIC for excess. Large stock dividends (25%+) use par value only. Stock splits change shares outstanding and par value proportionally with no journal entry and no effect on total equity.</p>",
