        cpaSection: "FAR",
        objectives: ["Distinguish changes in principle, estimate, and reporting entity","Apply retrospective and prospective treatment appropriately","Account for error corrections through restatement"],
        keyFormula: "Principle = Retrospective. Estimate = Prospective. Error = Restatement of prior periods.",
        lesson: "<p>A change in accounting principle (e.g., LIFO to FIFO) requires retrospective application: restate prior-period financial statements as if the new principle had always been used, and adjust beginning retained earnings of the earliest period presented for the cumulative effect (net of tax). Disclosures include the nature and reason for the change and the effect on each line item.</p><p>A change in accounting estimate (e.g., useful life, salvage value, allowance percentage) is applied prospectively to the current and future periods only. No restatement of prior periods. If a change in principle is inseparable from a change in estimate (e.g., changing depreciation method), it is treated as a change in estimate (prospective).</p><p>Error corrections require restatement of prior-period financial statements. The cumulative effect on periods before those presented is adjusted through opening retained earnings. Material errors must be restated. Immaterial errors may be corrected in the current period. A change in reporting entity (e.g., different subsidiaries in consolidation) requires retrospective application.</p>",
        practiceTip: "Principle = Retrospective. Estimate = Prospective. Error = Restatement. If principle and estimate are inseparable, treat as ESTIMATE (prospective)."
