        cpaSection: "FAR",
        objectives: ["Apply ASC 450 to loss and gain contingencies","Apply ASC 820 fair value measurement hierarchy","Account for asset retirement obligations under ASC 410"],
        keyFormula: "Loss: Probable + Estimable = Accrue. Range no best estimate = accrue minimum. FV Hierarchy: L1 > L2 > L3.",
        lesson: "<p>Under ASC 450, loss contingencies are classified as probable, reasonably possible, or remote. Probable and reasonably estimable losses are accrued. If a range exists with no best estimate, accrue the minimum and disclose the range. Reasonably possible losses are disclosed only (nature and estimate or statement that estimate cannot be made). Remote losses generally require no disclosure (except for guarantees).</p><p>Gain contingencies are NEVER accrued. They may be disclosed when probable, but the disclosure should avoid misleading implications of realization. This asymmetric treatment reflects conservatism.</p><p>ASC 820 defines fair value as an exit price in an orderly transaction. Level 1: quoted prices in active markets for identical items. Level 2: observable inputs for similar items, or identical items in inactive markets. Level 3: unobservable inputs using entity assumptions. Asset retirement obligations (ASC 410): record at fair value when incurred, with a corresponding increase in the related asset. The liability accretes over time using the credit-adjusted risk-free rate, and the capitalized cost is depreciated over the asset\u2019s remaining life.</p>",
        practiceTip: "Gain contingencies: NEVER accrue. Loss with range and no best estimate: accrue MINIMUM. Fair value = EXIT price, not entry price."
