        objectives: ["Distinguish Type I (recognized) from Type II (non-recognized) subsequent events","Determine the evaluation period for subsequent events","Apply disclosure requirements for significant subsequent events"],
        keyFormula: "Type I: conditions existed at balance sheet date = ADJUST. Type II: conditions arose after = DISCLOSE only.",
        lesson: "<p>ASC 855 requires evaluation of subsequent events through the date financial statements are issued (SEC filers) or available to be issued (non-SEC filers). Type I events provide additional evidence about conditions existing at the balance sheet date and require adjustment of the financial statements.</p><p>Examples of Type I events: settlement of litigation for an amount different from the accrual, loss on an uncollectible receivable due to customer bankruptcy that was deteriorating before year-end, or determination that an asset was impaired at year-end. These events require adjustment of the reported amounts.</p><p>Type II events are conditions arising after the balance sheet date. Examples: business combination after year-end, natural disaster, or issuance of debt or equity. These require disclosure of the nature and financial impact but no adjustment to the financial statements. The entity must disclose the date through which subsequent events were evaluated.</p>",
