        objectives: ["Apply Circular 230 requirements for practice before the IRS","Identify tax return preparer penalties under IRC Sections 6694 and 6695","Understand the tax research hierarchy and authoritative sources"],
        keyFormula: "Sec 6694(a): Unreasonable positions = greater of $1,000 or 50% of fee. Sec 6694(b): Willful/reckless = greater of $5,000 or 75% of fee.",
        lesson: "<p>Circular 230 governs practice before the IRS. Practitioners must exercise due diligence, not charge unconscionable fees, not delay matters, and return client records. Practitioners cannot sign a return unless there is a reasonable basis for the position (realistic possibility of success standard for undisclosed positions; reasonable basis with disclosure is the minimum).</p><p>Contingent fees are generally prohibited for preparing original tax returns, amended returns claiming refunds, or claims for credit. Contingent fees are permitted for IRS examination representation, claims filed during examination/audit, and judicial proceedings.</p><p>Tax return preparer penalties: IRC Section 6694(a) imposes penalties for unreasonable positions (greater of $1,000 or 50% of income from the return). Section 6694(b) imposes penalties for willful or reckless conduct (greater of $5,000 or 75% of income). Section 6695 covers procedural violations: failure to furnish copy, failure to sign, failure to provide identifying number. Sanctions under Circular 230 include censure, suspension, disbarment, and monetary penalties.</p>",
