        keyFormula: "Failure to file = 5%/month (max 25%). Failure to pay = 0.5%/month (max 25%). Accuracy-related = 20%.",
        lesson: "<p>The IRS examination process begins with an audit (correspondence, office, or field). If the taxpayer disagrees, they may appeal to the IRS Appeals Office. If unresolved, the taxpayer can petition the U.S. Tax Court (before payment), U.S. District Court (after payment), or U.S. Court of Federal Claims (after payment). Appeals from Tax Court go to the Circuit Court of Appeals, then potentially to the Supreme Court.</p><p>Failure to file penalty: 5% per month of the tax due, maximum 25%. Failure to pay penalty: 0.5% per month, maximum 25%. When both apply, failure to file is reduced by failure to pay. Accuracy-related penalty (Section 6662): 20% of underpayment due to negligence, substantial understatement (greater of 10% of tax or $5,000 for individuals), or substantial/gross valuation misstatement.</p><p>Statute of limitations: 3 years from the later of the filing date or due date for IRS assessment. Extended to 6 years if gross income is understated by more than 25%. No statute for fraud or failure to file. Refund claims must be filed within 3 years from filing or 2 years from payment, whichever is later.</p>",
