        lesson: "<p>Above-the-line deductions (for AGI): educator expenses ($300), HSA contributions, self-employment tax deduction (50% of SE tax), SEP/SIMPLE contributions, self-employed health insurance, penalty on early withdrawal of savings, student loan interest ($2,500 max), IRA contributions, and moving expenses (military only).</p><p>Standard deduction for 2026 (estimated, subject to H.R. 1 adjustments): Single approximately $15,000, MFJ approximately $30,000, HoH approximately $22,500. Additional amounts for age 65+ and blind. Itemized deductions: medical expenses exceeding 7.5% of AGI, state and local taxes (SALT) capped at $10,000 (note: H.R. 1 may increase the SALT cap), home mortgage interest on acquisition debt up to $750,000, charitable contributions (60% AGI for cash to public charities), casualty losses from federally declared disasters only.</p><p>Section 199A QBI deduction: up to 20% of qualified business income from domestic pass-through entities (partnerships, S corps, sole proprietorships). For taxpayers above income thresholds, the deduction is limited by the greater of: (a) 50% of W-2 wages, or (b) 25% of W-2 wages plus 2.5% of the unadjusted basis of qualified property. Specified service trades (health, law, accounting, consulting) are phased out above thresholds. QBI deduction is neither above-the-line nor an itemized deduction. H.R. 1 extends the QBI deduction provisions through 2028.</p>",
