        keyFormula: "Loss limitation order: 1) Tax basis 2) At-risk 3) Passive activity 4) Excess business loss. Each is sequential.",
        lesson: "<p>Loss limitations apply in a specific order. First, losses cannot exceed the taxpayer\u2019s tax basis in the activity. For partners, basis includes share of all liabilities. For S corp shareholders, basis includes only direct shareholder loans (not entity-level debt). Second, the at-risk rules limit losses to amounts the taxpayer has at risk (cash invested, adjusted basis of property contributed, amounts borrowed for which the taxpayer is personally liable, or qualified nonrecourse financing for real estate).</p><p>Third, passive activity losses can only offset passive income. Passive activities are trade or business activities in which the taxpayer does not materially participate. Seven material participation tests exist (500+ hours is the most common). Rental activities are generally passive regardless of participation, with a $25,000 special allowance for active participants (phased out between $100,000-$150,000 AGI). Real estate professionals are exempt from passive treatment if they meet the 750-hour and >50% tests.</p><p>The excess business loss limitation (Section 461(l)) disallows net business losses exceeding approximately $305,000 (single) or $610,000 (MFJ) for 2026. Excess becomes an NOL carryforward. Hobby losses (Section 183): if an activity is not engaged in for profit, deductions are limited to gross income from the activity. The presumption of profit applies if profitable in 3 of 5 years (2 of 7 for horse activities).</p>",
