        lesson: "<p>Book-tax differences arise because financial accounting (GAAP) and tax accounting (IRC) have different rules. Permanent differences never reverse: municipal bond interest (book income, not taxable), meals and entertainment (50% nondeductible for tax), life insurance premiums on officers (book expense, not deductible), fines and penalties, federal income tax expense.</p><p>Temporary differences reverse over time: depreciation (MACRS vs. GAAP creates DTL initially), prepaid income (taxable when received, book income when earned), warranty accruals (book expense when estimated, tax deduction when paid), bad debt expense (book when estimated under CECL, tax when specific write-off for small taxpayers).</p><p>Schedule M-1 reconciles book income to taxable income for corporations with total assets under $50 million. Schedule M-3 is required for corporations with total assets of $50 million or more and provides more detailed reporting of differences. M-1 format: start with net income per books, add unfavorable differences (book expenses not deductible, taxable income not on books), subtract favorable differences (book income not taxable, deductions not on books).</p>",
