        lesson: "<p>C corporations pay a flat 21% tax rate (TCJA). Key differences from individual taxation: no standard deduction, charitable contributions limited to 10% of taxable income (computed before DRD and charitable deduction), capital losses offset only capital gains (carryback 3 years, carryforward 5), organizational costs ($5,000 immediate deduction phased out at $50,000+ with remainder over 180 months).</p><p>The dividends received deduction (DRD) reduces triple taxation of corporate dividends: 50% for <20% ownership, 65% for 20-79% ownership, 100% for 80%+ ownership (affiliated group). The DRD is limited to the same percentage of taxable income (before DRD and NOL) unless the deduction creates or increases an NOL.</p><p>Post-TCJA NOLs carry forward indefinitely but are limited to 80% of taxable income. No carryback except for farming losses. Corporate estimated tax is required in four installments if tax exceeds $500. Large corporations (taxable income $1M+ in any of 3 preceding years) must use current-year liability for installments 2-4. State taxation: nexus established by physical presence or economic nexus (Wayfair decision). Apportionment formulas allocate income among states.</p>",
