        lesson: "<p>S corporation eligibility (Section 1361): domestic corporation, no more than 100 shareholders (family members treated as one), only individuals, estates, certain trusts, and tax-exempt organizations as shareholders, one class of stock (voting rights may differ), and no nonresident alien shareholders. Election requires consent of all shareholders on Form 2553.</p><p>S corporations compute ordinary income/loss and separately stated items (capital gains/losses, Section 1231 gains/losses, charitable contributions, tax-exempt income, investment income/expenses, foreign taxes). These items pass through to shareholders on Schedule K-1 based on per-share per-day allocation.</p><p>Shareholder basis in stock: initial investment + income allocations + additional contributions - distributions - loss allocations (cannot go below zero). Debt basis exists only for DIRECT shareholder loans to the corporation (not bank loans guaranteed by the shareholder). The accumulated adjustments account (AAA) tracks post-S election undistributed net income for S corps with prior C corp E&P. Distributions come from AAA first (tax-free return of basis), then from C corp E&P (dividend), then from remaining basis.</p>",
