        lesson: "<p>Partnerships are pass-through entities filing Form 1065. The partnership computes ordinary income/loss and separately stated items (same concept as S corps). Items pass through to partners on Schedule K-1 retaining their character. The partnership agreement controls allocations, which must have substantial economic effect under Section 704(b).</p><p>Partner basis includes the initial contribution plus share of all partnership liabilities (both recourse and nonrecourse). Recourse liabilities are allocated to the partner bearing economic risk of loss. Nonrecourse liabilities are allocated based on profit-sharing ratios (with adjustments for minimum gain and Section 704(c) gain). This is a KEY difference from S corps.</p><p>Guaranteed payments are payments to partners for services or use of capital determined without regard to partnership income. They are deductible by the partnership and ordinary income to the partner (like a salary for self-employment tax purposes). Non-liquidating distributions are generally tax-free to the extent of basis. Cash distributions exceeding basis create gain. Property distributions generally do not create gain (basis is the lesser of the property\u2019s basis or the partner\u2019s remaining basis).</p>",
