        lesson: "<p>The master budget includes operating budgets (sales, production, direct materials, direct labor, manufacturing overhead, SGA) and financial budgets (capital expenditures, cash budget, pro forma financial statements). The sales budget drives all other budgets. Production budget = expected sales + desired ending inventory - beginning inventory.</p><p>Static budgets are prepared for one level of activity. Flexible budgets adjust for actual activity levels, enabling meaningful variance analysis. Zero-based budgeting requires justifying every expense from zero each period. Activity-based budgeting allocates costs based on activity drivers rather than volume measures.</p><p>Forecasting techniques: qualitative (Delphi method, market research, executive opinion) and quantitative (regression analysis, time series, moving averages, exponential smoothing). Simple linear regression: Y = a + bX where b = slope (variable cost per unit) and a = intercept (fixed costs). R-squared measures the percentage of variation in Y explained by X. Higher R-squared indicates a better predictive model.</p>",
