        lesson: "<p>Net present value (NPV) discounts all expected cash flows at the required rate of return (usually WACC) and subtracts the initial investment. Positive NPV means the project adds shareholder value. Internal rate of return (IRR) is the discount rate making NPV zero. Accept if IRR exceeds the required return. For mutually exclusive projects, NPV is preferred over IRR when there are conflicts.</p><p>Payback period = time to recover the initial investment from cash flows. Simple payback ignores time value of money. Discounted payback uses PV of cash flows. Profitability index = PV of future cash flows / initial investment. Accept when PI > 1. PI is useful for capital rationing (rank by highest PI).</p><p>WACC = (E/V x Re) + (D/V x Rd x (1-T)). Cost of equity via CAPM: Re = Rf + Beta x (Rm - Rf). Valuation methods: DCF (present value of free cash flows), comparable company multiples (P/E, EV/EBITDA), and asset-based approaches. Terminal value often represents a significant portion of total value in DCF models.</p>",
