        lesson: "<p>Capital assets in government-wide statements include land, buildings, equipment, infrastructure (roads, bridges, sewer systems), and construction in progress. Depreciation is required unless the modified approach is used for infrastructure (maintain condition at established level with documented assessments). Capital assets are NOT reported in governmental fund financial statements; capital outlay is an expenditure.</p><p>Long-term liabilities (bonds, pension obligations, compensated absences, claims and judgments) are reported only in government-wide statements and proprietary fund statements. In governmental funds, bond proceeds are reported as other financing sources; debt service payments are expenditures. Bond premiums and discounts are handled differently at the fund level vs. government-wide.</p><p>Budgetary accounting: at the beginning of the fiscal year, record the adopted budget as Dr. Estimated Revenues, Cr. Appropriations, with the difference to Budgetary Fund Balance. Encumbrances track commitments: Dr. Encumbrances, Cr. Reserve for Encumbrances when the purchase order is issued. When goods are received, reverse the encumbrance and record the actual expenditure. Encumbrances are not GAAP expenditures but may be disclosed or restricted in fund balance.</p>",
