        objectives: ["Distinguish SOC 1, SOC 2, and SOC 3 report types and purposes","Apply Trust Services Criteria to SOC 2 engagements","Understand planning, testing, and reporting for SOC engagements"],
        keyFormula: "SOC 1 = financial reporting controls (ICFR). SOC 2 = Trust Services Criteria. SOC 3 = general use SOC 2 summary.",
        lesson: "<p>SOC 1 reports address controls at a service organization relevant to user entities\u2019 internal control over financial reporting (ICFR). Performed under SSAE 18/AT-C 320. Type I: opinion on design of controls at a point in time. Type II: opinion on design AND operating effectiveness over a period (minimum 6 months typically). Management provides a system description and assertion.</p><p>SOC 2 reports assess controls related to the Trust Services Criteria (TSC): Security (common criteria, always included), Availability, Processing Integrity, Confidentiality, and Privacy. SOC 2 reports are restricted-use documents provided to specified parties. SOC 3 reports are a general-use summary of a SOC 2 examination, providing a seal/report without detailed testing results.</p><p>SOC engagement planning: understand the service organization\u2019s system and services, identify applicable criteria, determine the scope and period, assess risks, and plan testing procedures. Testing methods: inquiry, observation, inspection, and reperformance. The service auditor\u2019s report includes: opinion on the description, design suitability (Type I/II), and operating effectiveness (Type II only). Complementary User Entity Controls (CUECs) and Complementary Subservice Organization Controls (CSOCs) are described but not tested.</p>",
