        cpaSection: "TCP",
        objectives: ["Apply advanced partnership provisions including Section 704(b) and hot assets","Calculate S corp built-in gains tax and LIFO recapture","Determine entity-level taxes for pass-through entities"],
        keyFormula: "Built-in gains tax: 21% on net recognized built-in gain during 5-year recognition period. Hot assets: Section 751(a) and (b).",
        lesson: "<p>Advanced partnerships: Section 704(b) requires that allocations have substantial economic effect. Capital accounts must be maintained, liquidating distributions must follow capital accounts, and partners must restore deficit capital accounts (or have a qualified income offset). Section 704(c) requires that built-in gains/losses on contributed property be allocated to the contributing partner.</p><p>Hot assets (Section 751): ordinary income assets (unrealized receivables and inventory). When a partner sells a partnership interest, gain attributable to hot assets is ordinary income regardless of the overall capital gain character. Section 751(b) applies to disproportionate distributions: if a partner receives more or less than their share of hot assets, the exchange is treated as a taxable transaction.</p><p>S corporation built-in gains tax: when a C corp converts to S status, net recognized built-in gains during the 5-year recognition period are subject to a 21% entity-level tax. LIFO recapture: C corps using LIFO that convert to S status must include the LIFO reserve in income over 4 years. S corps cannot have accumulated E&P unless they were formerly C corps. Excess passive investment income tax (Section 1375): 21% tax if S corp has C corp E&P and passive income exceeds 25% of gross receipts.</p>",
        practiceTip: "Hot assets = ordinary income on sale. Built-in gains tax: 5-year window, 21% rate. LIFO recapture: 4-year income inclusion on C-to-S conversion."
